2.4 Vapour Pressure of Liquid Solutions
Liquid solutions are formed when solvent is a liquid.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The solute can be a gas, a liquid or a solid.", "fibs": ["solute"]}
{"text": "Solutions of gases in liquids have already been discussed in Section 2.3.2.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "In this Section, we shall discuss the solutions of liquids and solids in a liquid.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "The solute may or may not be volatile.", "fibs": ["solute"]}
{"text": "We shall discuss the properties of only binary solutions, that is, the solutions containing two components, namely, the solutions of (i) liquids in liquids and (ii) solids in liquids.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "2.4.1 Vapour Pressure of Liquid-Liquid Solutions


Let us consider a binary solution of two volatile liquids and denote the two components as 1 and 2.", "fibs": ["Pressure"]}
{"text": "When taken in a closed vessel, both the components would evaporate and eventually an equilibrium would be established between vapour phase and the liquid phase.", "fibs": ["vessel"]}
{"text": "Let the total vapour pressure at this stage be ptotal and p1 and p2 be the partial vapour pressures of the two components 1 and 2 respectively.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "These partial pressures are related to the mole fractions x1 and x2 of the two components 1 and 2 respectively.", "fibs": ["mole"]}
{"text": "The French chemist, Francois Marte Raoult (1886) gave the quantitative relationship between them.", "fibs": ["chemist"]}
{"text": "The relationship is known as the Raoult’s law which states that for a solution of volatile liquids, the partial vapour pressure of each component of the solution is directly proportional to its mole fraction present in solution.", "fibs": ["relationship"]}
{"text": "Thus, for component 1
p1 ∝ x1
and p1 =  x1                                                                                                                  (2.12)
where  is the vapour pressure of pure component 1 at the same temperature.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "Similarly, for component 2
p2 = p20 x2                                                                                                   (2.13)
where p20 represents the vapour pressure of the pure component 2.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "According to Dalton’s law of partial pressures, the total pressure () over the solution phase in the container will be the sum of the partial pressures of the components of the solution and is given as:
ptotal = p1 + p2                                                                                                                    (2.14)
Substituting the values of p1 and p2, we get
ptotal = x1 p10 + x2 p20
= (1 – x2) p10 + x2 p20                                                                                  (2.15)
= p10 + (p20 – p10) x2                                                                                   (2.16)
Following conclusions can be drawn from equation (2.16).", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "(i) Total vapour pressure over the solution can be related to the mole fraction of any one component.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "(ii) Total vapour pressure over the solution varies linearly with the mole fraction of component 2.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii) Depending on the vapour pressures of the pure components 1 and 2, total vapour pressure over the solution decreases or increases with the increase of the mole fraction of component 1.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "A plot of p1 or p2 versus the mole fractions x1 and x2 for a solution gives a linear plot as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["plot"]}
{"text": "These lines (I and II) pass through the points for which x1 and x2 are equal to unity.", "fibs": ["x1"]}
{"text": "Similarly the plot (line III) of ptotal versus x2 is also linear (Fig.", "fibs": ["plot"]}
{"text": "The minimum value of ptotal is p10 and the maximum value is p20, assuming that component 1 is less volatile than component 2, i.e., p10 < p20.", "fibs": ["value"]}
