{"text": "2.4.3 Vapour Pressure of Solutions of Solids in Liquids
Another important class of solutions consists of solids dissolved in liquid, for example, sodium chloride, glucose, urea and cane sugar in water and iodine and sulphur dissolved in carbon disulphide.", "fibs": ["Pressure"]}
{"text": "For example, vapour pressure.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "We have learnt in Unit 5, Class XI, that liquids at a given temperature vapourise and under equilibrium conditions the pressure exerted by the vapours of the liquid over the liquid phase is called vapour pressure [Fig.", "fibs": ["learnt"]}
{"text": "In a pure liquid the entire surface is occupied by the molecules of the liquid.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "If a non-volatile solute is added to a solvent to give a solution [Fig.", "fibs": ["solute"]}
{"text": "(b)], the vapour pressure of the solution is solely from the solvent alone.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "This vapour pressure of the solution at a given temperature is found to be lower than the vapour pressure of the pure solvent at the same temperature.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "In the solution, the surface has both solute and solvent molecules; thereby the fraction of the surface covered by the solvent molecules gets reduced.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Consequently, the number of solvent molecules escaping from the surface is correspondingly reduced, thus, the vapour pressure is also reduced.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "2.4: Decrease in the vapour pressure of the solvent on account of the presence of solute in the solvent (a) evaporation of the molecules of the solvent from its surface is denoted by , (b) in a solution, solute particles have been denoted by  and they also occupy part of the surface area.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "The decrease in the vapour pressure of solvent depends on the quantity of non-volatile solute present in the solution, irrespective of its nature.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "For example, decrease in the vapour pressure of water by adding 1.0 mol of sucrose to one kg of water is nearly similar to that produced by adding 1.0 mol of urea to the same quantity of water at the same temperature.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Raoult’s law in its general form can be stated as, for any solution the partial vapour pressure of each volatile component in the solution is directly proportional to its mole fraction.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "In a binary solution, let us denote the solvent by 1 and solute by 2.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "When the solute is non-volatile, only the solvent molecules are present in vapour phase and contribute to vapour pressure.", "fibs": ["solute"]}
{"text": "Let p1 be the vapour pressure of the solvent, x1 be its mole fraction, pi0 be its vapour pressure in the pure state.", "fibs": ["p1"]}
{"text": "Then according to Raoult’s law
p1 ∝ x1
and p1 = x1                                                                                         (2.20)
The proportionality constant is equal to the vapour pressure of pure solvent, .", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "A plot between the vapour pressure and the mole fraction of the solvent is linear (Fig.", "fibs": ["plot"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "2.5 If a solution obeys Raoult’s law for all concentrations, its vapour pressure would vary linearly from zero to the vapour pressure of the pure solvent.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "2.5 Ideal and Non-ideal Solutions


Liquid-liquid solutions can be classified into ideal and non-ideal solutions on the basis of Raoult’s law.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "2.5.1 Ideal Solutions
The solutions which obey Raoult’s law over the entire range of concentration are known as ideal solutions.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The enthalpy of mixing of the pure components to form the solution is zero and the volume of mixing is also zero, i.e.,
∆mixH = 0 ,              ∆mixV = 0                                                                       (2.21)
It means that no heat is absorbed or evolved when the components are mixed.", "fibs": ["enthalpy"]}
{"text": "Also, the volume of solution would be equal to the sum of volumes of the two components.", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "At molecular level, ideal behaviour of the solutions can be explained by considering two components A and B.", "fibs": ["level"]}
{"text": "In pure components, the intermolecular attractive interactions will be of types A-A and B-B, whereas in the binary solutions in addition to these two interactions, A-B type of interactions will also be present.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "If the intermolecular attractive forces between the A-A and B-B are nearly equal to those between A-B, this leads to the formation of ideal solution.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "A perfectly ideal solution is rare but some solutions are nearly ideal in behaviour.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Solution of n-hexane and n-heptane, bromoethane and chloroethane, benzene and toluene, etc.", "fibs": ["bromoethane"]}
{"text": "fall into this category.", "fibs": ["fall"]}
{"text": "2.5.2 Non-ideal Solutions


When a solution does not obey Raoult’s law over the entire range of concentration, then it is called non-ideal solution.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "The vapour pressure of such a solution is either higher or lower than that predicted by Raoult’s law (equation 2.16).", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "If it is higher, the solution exhibits positive deviation and if it is lower, it exhibits negative deviation from Raoult’s law.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "The plots of vapour pressure as a function of mole fractions for such solutions are shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "Fig.2.6 The vapour pressures of two component systems as a function of composition (a) a solution that shows positive deviation from Raoult’s law and (b) a solution that shows negative deviation from Raoult’s law.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "The cause for these deviations lie in the nature of interactions at the molecular level.", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "In case of positive deviation from Raoult’s law, A-B interactions are weaker than those between A-A or B-B, i.e., in this case the intermolecular attractive forces between the solute-solvent molecules are weaker than those between the solute-solute and solvent-solvent molecules.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "This means that in such solutions, molecules of A (or B) will find it easier to escape than in pure state.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "This will increase the vapour pressure and result in positive deviation.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "Mixtures of ethanol and acetone behave in this manner.", "fibs": ["ethanol"]}
{"text": "In pure ethanol, molecules are hydrogen bonded.", "fibs": ["ethanol"]}
{"text": "On adding acetone, its molecules get in between the host molecules and break some of the hydrogen bonds between them.", "fibs": ["acetone"]}
{"text": "Due to weakening of interactions, the solution shows positive deviation from Raoult’s law [Fig.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "In a solution formed by adding carbon disulphide to acetone, the dipolar interactions between solute-solvent molecules are weaker than the respective interactions among the solute-solute and solvent-solvent molecules.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "This solution also shows positive deviation.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "In case of negative deviations from Raoult’s law, the intermolecular attractive forces between A-A and B-B are weaker than those between A-B and leads to decrease in vapour pressure resulting in negative deviations.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "An example of this type is a mixture of phenol and aniline.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "In this case the intermolecular hydrogen bonding between phenolic proton and lone pair on nitrogen atom of aniline is stronger than the respective intermolecular hydrogen bonding between similar molecules.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Similarly, a mixture of chloroform and acetone forms a solution with negative deviation from Raoult’s law.", "fibs": ["mixture"]}
{"text": "This is because chloroform molecule is able to form hydrogen bond with acetone molecule as shown.", "fibs": ["chloroform"]}
{"text": "This decreases the escaping tendency of molecules for each component and consequently the vapour pressure decreases resulting in negative deviation from Raoult’s law [Fig.", "fibs": ["tendency"]}
{"text": "(b)].", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Some liquids on mixing, form azeotropes which are binary mixtures having the same composition in liquid and vapour phase and boil at a constant temperature.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "In such cases, it is not possible to separate the components by fractional distillation.", "fibs": ["distillation"]}
{"text": "There are two types of azeotropes called minimum boiling azeotrope and maximum boiling azeotrope.", "fibs": ["azeotrope"]}
{"text": "The solutions which show a large positive deviation from Raoult’s law form minimum boiling azeotrope at a specific composition.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "For example, ethanol-water mixture (obtained by fermentation of sugars) on fractional distillation gives a solution containing approximately 95% by volume of ethanol.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Once this composition, known as azeotrope composition, has been achieved, the liquid and vapour have the same composition, and no further separation occurs.", "fibs": ["composition"]}
{"text": "The solutions that show large negative deviation from Raoult’s law form maximum boiling azeotrope at a specific composition.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "Nitric acid and water is an example of this class of azeotrope.", "fibs": ["acid"]}
{"text": "This azeotrope has the approximate composition, 68% nitric acid and 32% water by mass, with a boiling point of 393.5 K.

