{"text": "For example, the vapour pressure of an aqueous solution of sucrose is less than 1.013 bar at 373.15 K. In order to make this solution boil, its vapour pressure must be increased to 1.013 bar by raising the temperature above the boiling temperature of the pure solvent (water).", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Thus, the boiling point of a solution is always higher than that of the boiling point of the pure solvent in which the solution is prepared as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Similar to lowering of vapour pressure, the elevation of boiling point also depends on the number of solute molecules rather than their nature.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
