2.6.4 Osmosis and Osmotic Pressure
There are many phenomena which we observe in nature or at home.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "For example, raw mangoes shrivel when pickled in brine (salt water); wilted flowers revive when placed in fresh water, blood cells collapse when suspended in saline water, etc.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "If we look into these processes we find one thing common in all, that is, all these substances are bound by membranes.", "fibs": ["thing"]}
{"text": "These membranes can be of animal or vegetable origin and these occur naturally such as pig’s bladder or parchment or can be synthetic such as cellophane.", "fibs": ["animal"]}
{"text": "These membranes appear to be continuous sheets or films, yet they contain a network of submicroscopic holes or pores.", "fibs": ["network"]}
{"text": "Small solvent molecules, like water, can pass through these holes but the passage of bigger molecules like solute is hindered.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "Membranes having this kind of properties are known as semipermeable membranes (SPM).", "fibs": ["kind"]}
{"text": "If this membrane is placed between the solvent and solution as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["membrane"]}
{"text": "2.9, the solvent molecules will flow through the membrane from pure solvent to the solution.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "This process of flow of the solvent is called osmosis.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "2.9 Level of solution rises in the thistle funnel due to osmosis of solvent.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "The flow will continue till the equilibrium is attained.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "The flow of the solvent from its side to solution side across a semipermeable membrane can be stopped if some extra pressure is applied on the solution.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "This pressure that just stops the flow of solvent is called osmotic pressure of the solution.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "The flow of solvent from dilute solution to the concentrated solution across a semipermeable membrane is due to osmosis.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "The important point to be kept in mind is that solvent molecules always flow from lower concentration to higher concentration of solution.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "The osmotic pressure has been found to depend on the concentration of the solution.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "2.10: The excess pressure equal to the osmotic pressure must be applied on the solution side to prevent osmosis.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "The osmotic pressure of a solution is the excess pressure that must be applied to a solution to prevent osmosis, i.e., to stop the passage of solvent molecules through a semipermeable membrane into the solution.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "This is illustrated in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "Osmotic pressure is a colligative property as it depends on the number of solute molecules and not on their identity.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "For dilute solutions, it has been found experimentally that osmotic pressure is proportional to the molarity, C of the solution at a given temperature T. Thus:
π = C R T                                                                                                         (2.39)
Here π is the osmotic pressure and R is the gas constant.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "π = (n2 /V) R T                                                                                                 (2.40)


Here V is volume of a solution in litres containing n2 moles of solute.", "fibs": ["π"]}
{"text": "If w2 grams of solute, of molar mass, M2 is present in the solution, then n2 = w2 / M2 and we can write,

π V =                                                                                                  (2.41)
or M2 =                                                                                               (2.42)
Thus, knowing the quantities w2, T, π and V we can calculate the molar mass of the solute.", "fibs": ["w2"]}
{"text": "Measurement of osmotic pressure provides another method of determining molar masses of solutes.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "This method is widely used to determine molar masses of proteins, polymers and other macromolecules.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "The osmotic pressure method has the advantage over other methods as pressure measurement is around the room temperature and the molarity of the solution is used instead of molality.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "As compared to other colligative properties, its magnitude is large even for very dilute solutions.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "The technique of osmotic pressure for determination of molar mass of solutes is particularly useful for biomolecules as they are generally not stable at higher temperatures and polymers have poor solubility.", "fibs": ["technique"]}
{"text": "Two solutions having same osmotic pressure at a given temperature are called isotonic solutions.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "When such solutions are separated by semipermeable membrane no osmosis occurs between them.", "fibs": ["membrane"]}
{"text": "For example, the osmotic pressure associated with the fluid inside the blood cell is equivalent to that of 0.9% (mass/volume) sodium chloride solution, called normal saline solution and it is safe to inject intravenously.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, if we place the cells in a solution containing more than 0.9% (mass/volume) sodium chloride, water will flow out of the cells and they would shrink.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "Such a solution is called hypertonic.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "If the salt concentration is less than 0.9% (mass/volume), the solution is said to be hypotonic.", "fibs": ["salt"]}
{"text": "In this case, water will flow into the cells if placed in this solution and they would swell.", "fibs": ["case"]}
