{"text": "The concentration of a solution is expressed in terms of mole fraction, molarity, molality and in percentages.", "fibs": ["concentration"]}
{"text": "The dissolution of a gas in a liquid is governed by Henry’s law, according to which, at a given temperature, the solubility of a gas in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of the gas.", "fibs": ["dissolution"]}
{"text": "The vapour pressure of the solvent is lowered by the presence of a non-volatile solute in the solution and this lowering of vapour pressure of the solvent is governed by Raoult’s law, according to which the relative lowering of vapour pressure of the solvent over a solution is equal to the mole fraction of a non-volatile solute present in the solution.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "However, in a binary liquid solution, if both the components of the solution are volatile then another form of Raoult’s law is used.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Mathematically, this form of the Raoult’s law is stated as:.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "Solutions which obey Raoult’s law over the entire range of concentration are called ideal solutions.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Two types of deviations from Raoult’s law, called positive and negative deviations are observed.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Azeotropes arise due to very large deviations from Raoult’s law.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The properties of solutions which depend on the number of solute particles and are independent of their chemical identity are called colligative properties.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "These are lowering of vapour pressure, elevation of boiling point, depression of freezing point and osmotic pressure.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "The process of osmosis can be reversed if a pressure higher than the osmotic pressure is applied to the solution.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Colligative properties have been used to determine the molar mass of solutes.", "fibs": ["molar"]}
{"text": "Solutes which dissociate in solution exhibit molar mass lower than the actual molar mass and those which associate show higher molar mass than their actual values.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Quantitatively, the extent to which a solute is dissociated or associated can be expressed by van’t Hoff factor i.", "fibs": ["extent"]}
{"text": "This factor has been defined as ratio of normal molar mass to experimentally determined molar mass or as the ratio of observed colligative property to the calculated colligative property.", "fibs": ["factor"]}
